Move CI PyPI deployment after binary building In the past we had multiple cases where building the binaries on CI
failed for one reason or another.
This caused a problem since the PyPI upload used to happen in parallel
with building the binaries and therefore could happen despite the
binaries failed to build.

Additionally PyPI doesn't allow to overwrite a release, which then causes
problems in subsequent runs fixing the binary building.

Declare raiden to be typed via PEP561 When other packages import raiden, the raiden type signatures will not
be used by mypy unless that package declares itself as properly types.
This can be done via PEP561:
https://mypy.readthedocs.io/en/latest/installed_packages.html#using-pep-561-compatible-packages-with-mypy

Adding this will greatly improve type checking quality in
raiden-services (and potential other packages) whenever imports from
raiden are used.

Enforce checksummed address in geth_discover_next_available_nonce Web3 returns an `AttributeDict` that looks like this:

```
KeysView(AttributeDict({'10':
'0x50607A6053295b4d7E3A4F38242c5C0a3e47793a: 0 wei + 50000 gas
1000000000 wei', '100': '0x2C3154203f5127552664763D3053343d2f756151: 0
wei + 50000 gas 1000000000 wei',
```

And its addresses are not only hex, but they are also checksummed. As
such we need to also use checksummed addressed in this query or else
we will never get a correct response from geth.

Tightened version check. A upgrade may fail and leave a database with an old version behind,
however, it should never be the case that the current database has a
higher version number then the expected. Additionally, the existence of
the settings table with a version entry is necessary, otherwise the db
is corrupted.

Tightened version regex and fixed a bug The ordering of text containing numbers is not the same as the order of
the numbers themselves, this means the order of `9` and `10` will have
the unexpected result of making `10` smaller then `9`. This fixes it by
parsing the number and using natural order.

Fix Rest API affected by webargs CVE-2019-9710 The CVE description can be found
[here](https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2019-9710#vulnCurrentDescriptionTitle).

Essentially webargs JSON parsing uses a short-lived cache to store the parsed JSON body. This cache is not thread-safe, meaning that incorrect JSON payloads could have been parsed for concurrent requests.

Reorginized initialization code The code was split into side effect free, and effectful. The side effect
free code is named using the prefix `_initialize` as a convention, these
functions are preparing the node's state for proper operation. Effectful
functions are named with the prefix `_start` and start a subservice,
namely the alarm task or the transport layer, which are effectively
applying state from the outside world. The order in which these
functions have to be called is partially described by the use of asserts
that check for the expected state.

Note that the call to `first_run` is not effectful because the flag
`ready_to_process_events` is set to `False`.

Introduce CanonicalIdentifier As raised in #3493 we want to tighten the definition of what identifies
a channel.
This commit introduces the new type `CanonicalIdentifier` as a (named)
tuple of `(chain_identifier, token_network_address,
channel_identifier)`.

- In order to allow for a gradual introduction, I chose to use the
identifier with signed balance proofs first.
- In order to avoid migrations at this point in time, the identifier is
used as an `__init__` argument, but then destructured into the existing
fields.
- To minimize the amount of mypy casts introduced by this,
`CanonicalIdentifier.token_network_address` is typed as a union of
`TokenNetworkAddress` and `TokenNetworkID` for now.

For each batch unlock event, decide which side to unlock If the node has on-chain unlocked locks, then unlock partner locks
If the node has locked/unclaimed locks, then unlock our locks

Only unlock if the node gains back tokens The logic goes as follows:
For a receiver of a transfer, if there exists a transfer lock for which the
secret was revealed but the "unlocked" balance proof was not sent, and
the receiver registered the secret on-chain, then call unlock to get
this transfer's value.

For the sender of a transfer, if there exists one or more locks
which have not been unlocked or still unclaimed, then we try to unlock
to get back the locked amount of these locks

Waiting for all secret transactions to be mined If the user code is calling `register_secret` or `register_secret_batch`
it most likely expects the secret to be registered once the method
returns and if something goes wrong it probably expects an error. This,
however, was not the previous behavior, if there was an in-flight
transaction to register the secret the method just returned, regardless
of the status of the transaction and how long it would take for it to be
mined.

separating the `except` blocks, I was able to mute that problem.

Fixed Secret Registry Modifications to the variable open_secret_transactions have to be
synchronized, otherwise multiple execution threads will race and it's
possible that unecessary transactions are sent. This fixes the problem
by adding a semaphore to synchronize all threads, extends the
integration tests to properly test these edge race cases, and adds some
documentation explaining why the proxy is raising an unrecoverable
error.

form `is_secret_registered`.

guarantee that a node does not reuse a known secret. It first registered
the secret and then called `start_mediated_transfer_with_secret`. Because
the Raiden node was only querying the blockchain state from confirmed
blocks the recently registered secret was missed.

In this particular instance, using `latest` as a block_identifier is

particular call.

`gevent.Greenlet` in the list.
- `Matrix._get_retrier` always adds the `RetryQueue` item to its
internal mapping
    - If the `Matrix._stop_event` is set, the retrier is not started.
- During a call to `Matrix.stop` the first thing done is to set
`_stop_event`, and then the transport waits on the existing greenlets
and *retries*
- Because there is additional logic after setting the event and waiting
for the retriers which does context switch, a race existed which would
add an unstarted retrier to the transport mapping and wait on it.

Cleanup message class hierarchy PR #3374 introduced a potential DoS vector: since the message specified
a command-ID, it could be sent to a client (instead of a service).

Since clients expect a `message_identifier` for protocol messages, this
would lead to `AttributeError` on processing e.g. a `RequestMonitoring`
message in the client.

A couple of different traits of messages (has `message_identifier`, has
`sender`, has `signature`), so far were rather implicit. I introduced a
couple of message classes, to allow for explicit definition _and_ allow
re-use of `SignedMessage` in non Raiden-Off-Chain-Protocol messages
(i.e. `RequestMonitoring` or `UpdatePFS`, #3477).

Populate all ContractSend events with the blockhash at init There is a problem that this commits makes a temporary hack around.

For `ContractSendChannelClose` and for `ContractSendSecretReveal` only
in the case a mediator receives an offchain secret reveal we don't
have any way of getting the block hash. We have the block number, but
we can't make an I/O RPC call to get the blockhash from the block
number.

For these cases I temporarily give a blockhash of bytes(0). It
probably does not need to be checked when the event is processed. The
proper solution here would be to always have the block hash available
by adding it to the chain state along with the block number.

The commit which introduced this problem was
7e6dd0fd11aca00871556e1cdfa926fb2de415fa

It tried to fix the restart tests by resetting the alarm task's
`_stop_event` to `False`. Whenever a new alarm task is started during
tests.

The problem with this approach is that setting an `AsyncResult()` to
`False` at the very beginning, gives it a value. So by having a value
here:

https://github.com/raiden-network/raiden/blob/e76687c5d4dc8c6dd8888719ea60243f37c9a945/raiden/tasks.py#L151-L158

`self._stop_event.wait(sleep_time)` does not actually do any
sleeping. That's because the `AsyncResult` already has a value as we
can also see in the documentation
[here](http://www.gevent.org/api/gevent.event.html#gevent.event.AsyncResult.wait).

> If this instance already holds a value, it is returned immediately. If this instance already holds an exception, None is returned immediately.

Separate methods to handle state changes A Raiden node will be driven by two major drivers, the transport layer
and the rest api.

ATM tese two drivers have conflicting requirements on how to handle the
complete state change cycle. The Matrix transport layer does not want to
have exceptions raised, nor does it want to block and wait until a state
change is completely processed. The rest api OTOH wants to wait for the
completion of a given state change, and if an error happens it has to
catch it to properly report it to the user application.

For this reason a new code path was introduced, which exposes the errors
from the processing of transactions. Namely the processing of the close
transaction, which can throw and the message of the exception must be
exposed to the API caller.

4. Rename the old DB file to prevent Raiden from detecting it

fix unlock calls The token network smart contract has a few optimizations, one of these
optimizations is to remove storage data as soon as possible, to reduce
gas usage.

Because of that, once the channel is settled the channel structs and
their corresponding participant structs are removed. This removes the
following data from the smart contract:

participant.deposit
participant.withdraw
participant.is_the_closer
participant.balance_hash
participant.nonce

and

channel.settle_block_number
channel.state

Meaning the processing of unlock requests cannot rely on the
availability of the balance_hash and nonce data to find the
corresponding merkle tree. For a proper unlock the locksroot must be
used.

In the other hand, because of privacy concerns, the data provided to the
functions closed and updateTransfer is blinded, this is done to avoid
sharing the all the details with the monitoring service. Therefore the
event which request the call to settle, which has to find the complete
balance proof can not rely on the locksroot for the search, it must use
the balance_hash.

Because of the above, now we have four functions to search for the
channel data, two for our data, two for the partner data, one of each
for the call to settle and unlock.

Python API skipping WAL to close channels The work to offload waiting for transaction completion decoupled the
caller from the completion of a transactoin, this means that errors
which are informed through exceptions are raised on a different
location. This is problemation for the python api, since that
abstraction is used by the rest api, and without the exception there is
no simple way to inform the api caller what happened.

This sacrifices restartability of the close action in favor of better
error reporting.
simplified transaction management

simplified lock acquision in the python api - removed locks from the payment_channel proxy, since the token network
already has locks in place.
- Channel operations are no longer raising a ChannelBusy exception if
there is another concurrent operation. The new transaction will just
wait for the pending one to finish, and once the lock is held the
preconditions checks if the transaction is still valid.
    - This means that if a user request a channel close and there is a
    deposit in flight, the close will not raise an error but wait for
    the deposit to finish and then the close is run.
    - The same happens for the deposit waiting for a close, but the
    deposit is not sent once the lock is acquired because of the
    preconditions checks.

The above means we no longer need to acquire the locks for all channels
before doing a batch close, we can just dispatch the action close and
wait for the locks to be freed, and eventually the channels will close.

Organize order of estimateGas + call() for proxy transactions As discussed in Github [here](https://github.com/raiden-network/raiden/pull/2988#discussion_r247529028)
we are now using the following order for gas estimation and call() in
the smart contract proxy transactions:

```python
nonblockchain_preconditions()
blockchain_preconditions(consistent_block)  # this will also function as a check of the logic that lead us to start the call in the first place
gas = gas_estimate(pending_block)
if gas is not None:
  txhash = send_transaction()
  result = poll(txhash)
if gas is None or result is Failure:
    transaction_mined = gas is not None
    known_race, msg = check_blockchain_conditions(mined_block if transaction_mined else pending_block)
    if known_race:
        raise RaidenRecoverableError('{} {}'.format('Transaction Failed' if transaction_mined else 'Transaction will fail', msg))
    else:
        raise RaidenUnrecoverableError("Bad error -- we don't know why")
```

Handle the Parity Transaction already imported error Fix #3211 for parity.

What we do is:

1. When we get the transaction already imported error we get all the
pending transactions from the pool via `parity_allTransactions`.
2. Search these transactions for one originating from our node and
with the expected nonce.
3. i. If the transaction is found we get the hash and proceed as usual
with polling it.
   ii. If it's not found we handle this as the geth
   `TransactionAlreadyPending` error and crash raiden.

3-ii can only happen if the transaction gets out of the pool between
the time we get the already imported error and the time we query it. The only reason that 3-ii does not handle the situation gracefully is
due to the fact that there is no way to get the transaction hash and
at that point in the client we need a transaction hash so we are left
with no choice.

Add translator to WAL replay tool This adds a new option flag `-x --names-translator`. If it points to a
json file, it will translate all keys (ignore case) with the values when
printing attributes.

E.g.:
    -x names.json

```
cat names.json
{
    "0xb4f44cd22a84DE0774B802e422D4c26A73Dd68d7": "initiator",
    "0x7f9902e21747AC5DABbd9Ba50E96F3b1f58Ae639": "mediator",
    "0x4B2F10eC7edc602915CE7db3547fc3352B09401C": "target",
    "0x0Ea30825657A15a8460bc025AA0608AB3405d585": "RTT"
}
```
will lead to output like this:
```
> ActionChangeNodeNetworkState
```

After refund transfer with no new routes don't delete payment task After the initiator receives a RefundTransfer and has no new routes to
forward the payment the payment should fail but the payment task
should not be removed.

The reasoning behind this is that the mediator who sent us the refund
transfer does not know that the payment is canceled and keeps it on
his state until lock expiration. So he will eventually also send us a
`LockExpired` message when the lock expires.

We need to have the initiator payment task alive at that point or else
we will not process the LockExpired and see the nonce mismatch
problems described in #3146 which will lead to the channel getting stuck.

Related to the comment in
https://github.com/raiden-network/raiden/issues/3146#issuecomment-447378046

Bugfix: Before settle the locksroot is unknown The code which calls unlocks used to search for the balance proof
through the locksroot value, this works for unlock, however it does not
work for calls to settle, since at that point in time the smart contract
only knowns about the balance_hash.

Instead of adding two new functions which do pretty much the same thing,
I decided to rely on the fact that balance_hash is collision resistent
and it contains the locksroot, meaning that a search for either value
should work, and as of version v0.8.0 of the smart contracts the balance
hash is available for when both function calls are done.

Fix Refund transfer serialization The shape of messages which balance proofs changes depending if it
contains a lock or not. Messages like Unlock, LockExpired and
DirectTransfer have a balance proof directly in the object itself, while
messages like LockedTransfer and RefundTransfer have their balance proof
inside a transfer object, which also contains the lock.

This difference in the shape of the objects would also require different
queries to the database. In order to not have such queries, the
serialization of the objects duplicates information, and copies the
balance proofs from the inner transfer object to the top level, allowing
a single query to work with all the above messages and their state
changes counter part.

However, such strategy is error prone, and we indeed forgot to properly
serialize two state changes, namely ReceiveTransferRefundCancelRoute and
ReceiveTransferRefund which are used for refund transfers. In this case,
if a refund transfer was the last transfer received for a given channel,
and this channel was closed, the call to settlement fails, because the
corresponding balance proof cannot be found.

This commit adds a new marker for the state changes which have a balance
proof, fixes the serialization of the refund state changes, and adds a
unit test for the current state changes which have a balance proof.

Try to handle estimateGas predicting that a call will fail After the changes introduced by
https://github.com/raiden-network/raiden/pull/2623/ we again rely on gas
estimation for the gas limit to provide to an onchain call which is great since
it reduces our overall ETH balance requirements.

But we don't take into account the fact that if estimateGas returns None it's
because the transaction will fail, either due to our account not having enough
funds or because the call will just revert somewhere down the line due to the
contract logic (e.g. calling settle before closing).

With that in mind we can now detect those bad cases a bit earlier and handle
them without sending an onchain transaction. This is what this PR is trying to achieve.

Address PR review

Transaction handled by inidividual greenlets To avoid starvation of the AlarmTask, the handling of raiden events must
be done in separated threads.

Ideally transactions would be added to a queue, allowing them to be
batched, however this requires support from the JSON RPC client, which
is not available, so currenlty we are implicitely queing the
transactions in greenlets and the order in which the transactions are
mined.

For the off-chain messages the queues are in place, and it's sufficient
to just queue them using send_async. Note, however, it's very important
for the messages to be queue in order, for this reason greenlets are
/not/ used when there is an event for a protocol message. If greenlets
where to be used, the order of messages could change, and if a message
with a higher nonce got added to the queue first, then the queue would
stuck.

bugfix: Proper life cycle for the mediator The mediator task must be kept around while the mediated lock is present
in any of the used channels. This is necessary because eventually either
the lock will be unlocked or expire, and the corresponding messages
which remove the lock from the corresponding merkle tree must be
handled.

The code was ignoring this rule for a transfer which could *not* be
forwarded. The corresponding channel which received the message was
being forgotten, and the task cleared when the other channels where
properly finalized.

A mediator would fail to forward the transfer if there where no usable
routes. A route would be considered unusable for a number of different
reasons:

- The channel was closed on-chain
- The node didn't have enough capacity to forward the transfer at the
moment the lock was received
- The partner node was considered offline at the moment the transfer was
received
- The channels which didn't fit the above criteria where tried already.

This added the received transfer, which could not be forwarded, as a
waiting transfer, and the clearing of the task is now also checking for
the status of the lock in the channel which received the waiting
transfer.

Fix flaky test_batch_unlock Only in Travis test_batch_unlock failed some times flakily with the following
[logs](https://gist.github.com/LefterisJP/61827579badbc759a6e25bea28a70f6c).

What happens is that the attempted transfer

```
[<HashTimeLockState amount:10 expiration:55 secrethash:88b432dc>]
0x88b432dc032ca2fdcc6b98a9bc0cb539f68f40971523e5698aa2f5fc28804097
```

has a lock expiration of `55`.

But according to the logs

```
2018-10-26 23:05:21 [debug    ] Received new block             [raiden.tasks] block_hash=0x875b1450d0ca06114aafaba0f3f85a90a874ad5133ad58d8b28cf9bee33a5681 gas_limit=9492431 number=55
2018-10-26 23:05:21 [debug    ] State change                   [raiden.raiden_service] node=03ced6e8 state_change={"block_number": 50, "gas_limit": 9538911, "block_hash": "0xc3058ae034198402d893837f70c04a7c2bd2e0758cfcd894ce9b3bc601cecbbe", "_type": "raiden.transfer.state_change.Block", "_version": 0}
2018-10-26 23:05:21 [info     ] registerSecretBatch successful [raiden.network.proxies.secret_registry] contract=eda9cc0e node=03ced6e8 secrethashes=['0x88b432dc032ca2fdcc6b98a9bc0cb539f68f40971523e5698aa2f5fc28804097'] secrethashes_not_sent=[]
2018-10-26 23:05:22 [debug ] Received new block [raiden.tasks]
block_hash=0x5bb88b56572c1180987a74bc9e835dade0b82342f48d70c13486e1c0588573ed
gas_limit=9483231 number=56
```

the client seems to be 1 block late to send the register secret transaction. So
in the end after batch unlock the initiator gets the tokens back instead of the target.

Since this started right after the change to [confirmed block
emitting](https://github.com/raiden-network/raiden/pull/2895/commits/2691264dbe5d3ec3b59aa22db887bfd183f335f4)
it's safe to assume that this happens because there is an introduced delay of 5
blocks for all actions when it comes to the blockchain. This should be properly
addressed when #2885 is implemented. Until then the tests had a reveal timeout
pretty close to the default number of confirmation blocks which lead to this
flaky test failing some times.

So the fix is to change the reveal timeout for tests to adjust for the default
number of confirmation blocks.

bugfix: Mediator task must wait for expired lock The mediator task definition of finalized was wrong. The task was
considered final the lock expired, which happens once the corresponding
block was mined.

The consequence is that during a run where the lock expired, the
mediator would send the remove expire lock message, and set the status
of the task as finalized, leading the task to be cleared. The problem is
that the mediator task is also responsible to handle the remove expired
lock messages, and if is clered these messages are not handled, leading
to synchronization problems among the participants.

Merge pull request #2882 from LefterisJP/make_mainnet_default_network_id Switch default network_id to mainnet

Fix race condition with new blocks and filters The race happened under this circunstance:

- A node learns about a new block, updates its state, then crashes
- On restart, the block number is recovered, the filters are
  installed with the latest known block.
- The race: The node finishes the above before a new block is mined
- The bug: The filter is polled during start of the RaidenService, by
  calling the AlarmTask.first_run, which always executes the
  callbacks, eventually using the StateFilter's to poll for new events
  from a block in the future.

The fix was to give the latest known block number to the alarm task in
the as an argument for first_run, and only execute the callbacks if
there is a new block.

bugfix: InitChain must use deployed blocknumber - During start Raiden uses the latest block number (as seen by the
  node's Ethereum node) to initialize the node's state, this value
  is dispatched and made recoverable by the WAL with the ActionInitChain
  state change.
- Then all events are polled starting from block 0 until the current
  block number, updating the node's view of the blockchain.
- Assuming the node crashes during polling. On restart it will use the
  block number set by ActionInitChain instead of 0, which is up the latest
  block number, effectively missing events not processed after the crash.

This also fixes the value 0, which should not be used. The correct value is
the block height at which the token network registry was deployed, which
is available in the RaidenService.query_start_block

delayed expired lock removal the receiver of a lock expired message must wait for the confirmation
blocks before accepting the message, otherwise the secret could have
been registered on a reorg which is unknown to the node.

The sender must take this into account, and only send the remove expired
lock after the confirmation blocks has elapsed, with a few caveats:

- the confirmation blocks is a local configuration, meaning the sender
may have a lower value than the receiver, and the queue will be stalled
until the target's node requirement is met.
- waiting for confirmation blocks is not sufficient, because the
sender's blockchain may be "more in synch" then the target's chain. IOW,
the target's chain may be slightly behind from the chain's HEAD, and
from its perspective the lock has not yet expired.

Because of the second point above, the sender (as an initiator and/or
mediator), is now waiting for confirmation blocks * 2.

tests: removed flakiness test_lock_expiry used blocks as a proxy to estimate when a remove
expired lock message was sent, this was a source of flakiness when the
message was not sent in the expected time. This adds a custom message
handler to track when messages are received, allowing the test to
proceed only when the expected state is reached.

Makes HTTPExecutor wait for no process to be listening on port on stop Sometimes, between kill/stop and the synapse socket which listens in the port
to be closed, there may be a small delay, which prevented the next
synapse instance to run. This commit includes the check for a running
process in the given port for running(), so stop() will wait for no
process to be listening on that port, and then kill-9 it if it lasts
more than 10s. In practice, it should just wait a little more before
exiting. Synapse test server is used only in tests, with :memory: db, so
no need to be kind to it

Added protocol version to the Ping message The protocol version handshake should be tied to the healthcheck in
order to avoid race conditions. Where a target is known to be online but
its protocol version is unknown.

Without the version in the Ping message the sender must assume the
lowest protocol version, otherwise a message unknown o the target could
be sent. Because the new message is not known to the target, it would
never be processed, and the message queue for that channel would stall.

Adding this field to the Ping message fixes the above problem. This is
being added now just to introduce the strategy of protocol handshake for
future releases.

events: only poll confirmed events Reorgs can introduce duplicated events in the system, and it has been
experienced in the past with a close transaction. To handle reorgs there
are two options:

- Raiden should not poll for events from the latest block, but only from
latest - confirmation blocks.
- Raiden keeps in sync with latest, and if necessary also fork locally
by replaying the state changes.

The first option has the adavantage of being simpler to implement, while
the second allows Raiden to react faster to some events, e.g. secret
being registered in the registry.

This commit implements the first.

fix: don't use blockgas limit as startgas Integration tests are flaky because the current code base is using a
percentage of the block gas limit as the transaction startgas (cached
for 600 seconds). This is a problem when there are too few transactions
and the gas limit decreases by more than 20%, making the transaction
sent invalid and consectuvily the ethereum node rejects it with a
'exceeds block gas limit' message.

For the version v0.4.0 of the smart contract these functions have a
predictable gas profile and can use hard coded constats:

- EndpointRegistry:registerEndpoint
- TokenNetworkRegistry:createERC20TokenNetwork
- TokenNetwork:closeChannel
- TokenNetwork:updateNonClosingBalanceProof
- SecretRegistry:registerSecret
- SecretRegistry:registerSecretBatch

For these functions we call external smart contracts that can have a
variable gas usage, therefore must be estimated.

- TokenNetwork:openChannel -> uses token.balanceOf
- TokenNetwork:setTotalDeposit -> uses token.balanceOf and
token.transferFrom
- TokenNetwork:setTotalWithdraw -> uses token.transfer
- TokenNetwork:settleChannel -> uses token.transfer
- TokenNetwork:unlock -> uses token.transfer
- TokenNetwork:cooperativeSettle -> uses token.transfer

The proxies were updated to use a gas estimation when it makes sense,
similar to what was introduced by 454671a64fdff090049a32fcea2f3fd8cbb19925.

The estimate_and_transact function was broken by the byzantium release
and fixed with the max gas limit by 1f18640253cc30f1ed21c9d618ceb06a1d764a5d,
which was removed from the code base by f1d055c296e4d5dd4fff8781c2c2a1590076a830
and implicitely changed the code to use the block gas limit.

logging: logs before & after all transactions To make debugging easier some of the proxies have logs for before and
after the transaction is sent. This adds these logs lines to the missing
proxies.

The general guidelined followed was:
- logs prior to the transaction sent are debugging logs
- logs after the transaction is mined are:
  - critical if the transaction failed in an unrecoverable manner
  - info if the transaction failed in a recoverable manner
  - info if the transaction was successful
- the logs are formatedd with `<smart_contract_function_name> <state>`,
where state is one of these:
  - called
  - failed
  - successful

This did improve the logging but it's not covering all cases, specially
the checks done in the channel proxy which can raise an exception

Implement http status code matching All Raiden API tasks now take an `expected_http_status` argument
which defaults to `2..` and is parsed as a regex (integers are also accepted).
If the API call's http status doesn't match the regex a
`RESTAPIStatusMismatchError` exception is raised.

This can be used to test for various failure cases.

Simplified the filter polling The default implementation of filters provided by web3.py rely on the
ethereum node to keep the state of the from_block number. Although this
is convenient it's a problem when either the Ethereum or Raiden node are
restarted, because the previous block number must be remembered to
re-install the filter.

Since the from_block needs to be known anyways instead of relying on the
remote ethereum node to know the from_block the stateless filter was
introduced, which always rely on the start_block number being known.

This just removes the unused code which supported the web3.py Filter
class.

problems:

followed by `start`, but the rest api needs special logic to give to
`start` the host and port arguments.
2. It's easy to mess up if one forgets to pass around the host port pair
with the intance the restart will end up with server in the wrong port.

From above, 2. the reason for some flakyness in the crash stress test,
where part of the test is to force failure in the REST API by restarting
it, but without the configuration the server changed ports and ended up
causing port conflicts (when two servers were restarted and both tried

target: deliver once semantics Recap: To avoid having to rewrite messages, the recipient of a message
must accept a valid message for an expire transfer. This is required
because a sender may be online and try to send a transfer through a node
which just went offline, when the node comes back online the transfer's
lock could have enterred the danger zone or have expired, but the sender
did not rewrite its message queue. In this case the recipient's channel
must validate the received balance proof, but not the transfer, and the
corresponding task (either mediator or target), **must not** continue
with the protocol if the current block is after the start of the danger
zone.

This however, doesn't mean the same message must be processed twice.
It's important for a node to have deliver once semantics, which is
achieved by the retry logic in the sender, with the sequential nonce in
the receiver, which is part of the balance proof.

This commit fixed the target task, to processed the balance proof only
once. And it keeps the logic to accept transfers with an expired lock,
allowing nodes to properly synchronize.

[ci integration]

channel: factored out balance proof validation Each message that contain a balance proof must validate:

- the chain_id
- the token_network_id
- the channel_id
- the transferred_amount + locked_amount won't overflow
- the recovered address from the signature
    - which must be computed form a valid datahash (chain_id,
      token_network_id, channel_id, balance_hash, additional_hash)

Direct messages must additionally:
- the locked amout must not change
- the locksroot must not change
- the transferred amount must increase
- and the transferred amount must increase at maximum by the sender's
node capacity

Locked messages must additionally:
- the locked amout must change increse by the new lock's amount
- the locksroot include the new lock
- the new merkle tree must be smaller than the maximum size
- the transferred amount must not change
- and the locked amount must increase at maximum by the sender's
node capacity

Removed Expired Lock messages must additionally:
- the locked amout must decrease exactly by the expired lock's amount
- the locksroot remove the expired lock
- the transferred amount must not change

Unlock messages must additionally:
- the locked amout must decrease exactly by the unlocked lock's amount
- the locksroot remove the unlocked lock
- the transferred amount increase exactly by the unlocked lock's amount

changes for this.

udp: passing the address explicitely - The transport class is an injectable dependency for the raiden service,
because of this the transport is initialized before raiden service
- The alarm task is primed before starting the transport layer, this is
required because the Raiden node needs to be synchronized with the
latest on-chain state before accepting messages (otherwise valid
messages would be rejected, e.g. a transfer for a channel opened while
the node was offline)
- The alarm may poll a channel new event, which starts a healtcheck
task, because the healtcheck task required the raiden instance to get
the address the node was crashing.

bugfix: start_health_check_for must be a noop on start

The transport start_health_check must not be called if the transport is
not started, because the healthcheck task assumes the raiden service is
fully available.

Because of this, the function start_health_check_for needs to be a noop
during the raiden service startup. The healtcheck for the partner nodes
discovered through the start phase is done by start_neighbours_healthcheck.

Forcing constant expiration time through the path In the first interation of Raiden unlock had to be called on a per
channel basis, and the operation was only allowed for a channel on the
closed state. Because the unlock was on a per channel basis, every
mediator had to use a lower expiration for the lock it sent in respect
to the lock it received.

The hash-time-lock expiration was always decrease by a configuration
variable named reveal timeout, the setting was in number of blocks, and
represented how many blocks were required by the node to learn about an
on-chain unlock on the payee channel, and call unlock on the payer
channel. The reveal timeout setting included how many blocks the node
requires to learn about a new confirmed block, for the payee unlock,
plus how many blocks were required to successfully mine two
transactions, the close and the unlock on the payer channel.

The above dynamics changed with the introduction of the secret registry.
With the secret registry the channel no longer needs to be closed in
order to unlock a lock, once the secret is registered this information
can be used by the channel smart contract to unlock the any
hash-time-lock on-chain. Additionally the secret registry allowed the
lock for *all* mediators to be unlocked at the same time, this
difference turns out to be crucial.

With the secret registry, the semantics of the reveal timeout changed
from the time to learn about a new block and to mine two trasanctions,
to just the time required to mine the secret registration transaction.

The secret registration happens if a node learns about the secret
off-chain while the hash-time-lock is in the danger zone, where the
danger zone is a block close enough to the lock's expiration in which it
may take too long for the secret to be registered in time, becaase of
the risk of losing the payment, the node must send a transaction to
register the secret on-chain.

The above means a node will send a secret register transaction
regardless of how many blocks are left for the expiration of lock, be it
unhappy case of a single block or the happy case of `reveal_timeouts`
blocks. The rationale is that a node wants to receive the payment, and
if the locks is nearing expiration it should try to register the secret
to secure the payment. (Note that the unhappy case can be improved, but
the race condition cannot be fixed)

As a consequence, if the lock expiration decreases through the route, as
it was done with the first iteration, the secret registration may happen
too late for hop which sent the transaction, but soon enough for
previous hops. This means that for a path like A-B-C, the node C can
learn about a secret at block `n` which is `5` apart from the lock's
expiration, and the transaction can be mined at block `n+6`, C will not
receive the payment but if the lock expiration for A-B was larger B can
receive the payment.

The fix is to make lock's expiration constant. The initiator is
responsible to choose a value that is sufficiently large to allow a
transfer to be routed through the network without expiring, and low
enough so that it's not reject by too many channels with a low
settlement timeout. Once the target receive the hash-time-lock it must
include the lock's expiration in the secret request, which in turn is
verified by the transfer initiator, where it's of interest of the
initiator to make sure the expiration was constant through out the path,
otherwise the target would be at risk of not receiving the transfer.

Set higher default logging levels on root logger Usually, we want the loggers to aways have level=DEBUG, so everything
passes by it and are filtered on the handlers filters instead of the
logger filter. But, although the handlers filters works fine for the
default stream/file handler and debug-file handlers, everything is
catched by pytest catch-all logs, producing a massive spam of logging
entries in pytest.
This change ensures only the `raiden` logger gets set to DEBUG, and the
root logger is set to the minimum log level of the handlers, defaulting
to INFO and doing initial filtering on the logger too, avoiding pytest
log spam.

[ci integration]

Fixed race for proxies instantiation It's really important that each Raiden instance only used one proxy per
smart contract, otherwise the proxy synchronization wont work. The token
network proxy is an example, where the proxy needs locking to forbid
concurrent deposits (to avoid races with the ERC20 allowance).

To enforce a singleton proxy the blockchain service is used as a proxy
factory. The problem was that each proxy constructor checks the
blockchain data, which does IO and allows another greenlet to run, this
made it possible for races among two greenlets that need the same proxy.

Tho fix the above race coarse locks were added to protected the
instantiaton of each type of proxy.

Removed flaky The flaky package allows a failling test to be automatically re-executed
a number of times.

The package is quite useful but we are not using it anymore, and the
flaky plugin is messing up the stack trace of a failing test.

JSONRPCClient nonce simplification - Updating the nonce from the ethereum client is useless if there is no
synchronization among clients, where a client may be another app or
JSONRPCClient instance. Because of this the logic to update the local
nonce view was removed, either the Raiden node should fully control the
account and only one JSONRPCClient instance per private key is used, or
remote signing should be used.
- To debug nonce problems, i.e. transaction replacement errors, it's
necessary to know if there is more than one JSONRPCClient instance per
account or if the locking mechanism is not working properly. For the
first case a debug log was added in the JSONRPCClient constructor, for
the latter the send raw transaction was wrapped with log lines to make
it easier to detect concurrent calls.

Properly synchronizing the raiden node with the BC During startup all filters must be queried to synchronize the node's
state. This must be done after the node's state is primed (either
initialized or restored from a snapshot), the filters are installed, and
prior to the transport being started.

This changes:
- `install_and_query_all_blockchain_filters` was using
`RaidenService.get_block_number` as the value for the filters
`to_block`, which is not updated until the alarm task is executed,
meaning the node's state was not updated before the AlarmTask was
scheduled.
- Removed from the `AlarmTask` an unused attribute named `response_queue`
- Removed the buggy sleep timeout computation from the `AlarmTask` (the
work_time was always zero)
- Inlined the method poll_for_new_block in the AlarmTask loop
- Added a check if the chain_id of the underlying ethereum node changes

Removed block_number from the events storage The block number is provided through the
RaidenService.handle_state_change function, the block number used in
this function varies with the type of the state change.

Events from the blockchain can use a consistent value (the block number
from the event), but state changes for user actions or protocol messages
must use the current block number known by the node, which will vary on
restart. To avoid inconsistencies on the block_number on restarts, this
value was removed.

Fixed unlock event handling This PR is introducing a second filter for netting channel events. This
was necessary because with only one filter some events were missing.

The filter which missed events was setup with the following topics:

  [
     [None, channel_i],
     [ChannerlUnlock, participant1, participant2],
     [ChannerlUnlock, participant2, participant1],
  ]

With the above topic, the filter was *not* returning the event
ChannelSettled. The ChannelSettled event *was* returned with the
following topic:

  [[None, channel_id]]

Therefor, one of the instaleed filters use the topic above. In order to
get the Unlock events a second filter is installed with the following
topic:

  [
     [ChannerlUnlock, participant1, participant2],
     [ChannerlUnlock, participant2, participant1],
  ]

Using two filters was sufficient to get all events, but it is also
returning duplicated ChannelSettled events. The reason for this is
unknown, but the code is properly handling the duplicated events.

reenabled the debugger hook for pytest sessions The previous implementation was hooking on the print_exception instead
of handle_error and allowed nested calls to pdb, which made it
impossible to quit the pdb session once the post_mortem was done,
because of that it was removed.

This tries to improve on the previous strategy, using the exposed
`handle_error` interface from the hub, which is intedend to be
overwritten, and by disallowing nested calls to pdb, which should both:

- allow a session to quit
- stop "randomly" jumping around different greenlets, if there are
multiple exceptions being raised

ERC20 approve/transferFrom calls must be ordered [ci integration]

The fixtures `raiden_network` and `raiden_chain` execute deposits for
different channels in parallel to speed up the test setup.

With the new smart contracts all the channels share the same token
network address, in contrast to the old version of the smart contracts
wich had a smart contract per channel. As a consequence the fixture
setup started racing with the approve and deposit calls.

For a test were the following topology is used A-B-C, the node B must
deposit for both the channel A-B and B-C, both of these deposits are
done with the token network smart contract, and required a call to
approve to set up the allowance, followed by a call to setTotalDeposit
to do the actual channel deposit.

This specific ordering:

- approve
- approve
- setTotalDeposit
- setTotalDeposit

resulted in an error, were the second call to approve overwrote the
previous allowance, the first call to setTotalDeposit consumed all
allowance leaving the second transaction without an allowance, making it
fail.

Fixed the call to settle The smart contract function `settleChannel` enforces order of the
arguments based on sum of transferred and locked amount.

    function settleChannel(
        address participant1,
        uint256 participant1_transferred_amount,
        uint256 participant1_locked_amount,
        bytes32 participant1_locksroot,
        address participant2,
        uint256 participant2_transferred_amount,
        uint256 participant2_locked_amount,
        bytes32 participant2_locksroot
    )

These values must correspond to two valid balance proofs
(TokenNetwork.sol:504):

    require(verifyBalanceHashData(
        participant1_state,
        participant1_transferred_amount,
        participant1_locked_amount,
        participant1_locksroot
    ));
    require(verifyBalanceHashData(
        participant2_state,
        participant2_transferred_amount,
        participant2_locked_amount,
        participant2_locksroot
    ));

And the sum of the transferred and locked amount of the second
participant (TokenNetwork.sol:915-925):

    participant1_max_transferred = failsafe_addition(
        participant1_settlement.transferred,
        participant1_settlement.locked
    );
    participant2_max_transferred = failsafe_addition(
        participant2_settlement.transferred,
        participant2_settlement.locked
    );

Must be larger than the sum for the first (TokenNetwork.sol:929):

    require(participant2_max_transferred >= participant1_max_transferred);

fixed regression The variables SYSTEM_ERROR and NOT_ERROR are configured differently in
the raiden client and the test cases, this is required because the
raiden client is adopting is crash only, meaning the process should quit
on any exception that is unhandled, which is not useful for tests, since
we want to execute the whole test suite even if an exception is not
handled.

For this reason the variables must overwritten only for the tests run,
which is done by the fixture `dont_exit_pytest`, the top-level assigment
is a bad idea since just importing the module will change the
global state, and this could be done on a normal run, effectively
breaking the assumption that raiden is crash only.

Split channel setup in two steps First the apps which will have a channel are choosen, then the channel
is open and a deposit is made.

The split was such that each channel can be open and initialized by a
separated greenlet, and the routine to wait for the channel was extended
to also wait for the deposit.

Replaced Processed by the Delivered message The Delivered message is used to guarantee the message is saved to disk,
but a saved message is not necessarily valid. The Processed message is
used for messages that may have conflicts because of the eventual
consistency of the blockchain. Any message that have data which is
validated against the blockchain state, like a balance proof that must
check the on-chain deposit, must use the Procesed response to inform the
sender that the received message was considered valid, and as a
consequence that ethereum have reached eventual consistency.

- Using the message id and queue name provided by the events.
- Delivered and Processed are use for the protocol level messages, which
make them unsuiteble for a Ping response. Thus the Pong message was
added.
- Only sending the Processed message was guarded against a closed
socket, this also changed the queue processing to check if the socket is
open before using it.
Added registry to all APIs and function calls

Added Delivered message The Delivered message is used by the receiver to inform the sender that
the message has been saved. Used for transports like TCP and UDP, that
don't guarantee message persistence.

Most messages sent to another node must be processed, otherwise the
sender and reciver nodes will get out of sync. To guarantee that a
message is processed it must be persisted, otherwise under power faults
the message is lost, therefor the sender must keep the message around
until the receiver has confirmed the message is saved.

With a naive implementation, where messages are discarded by the sender
with just an acknowledgement instead of persistence, the recipient node
may fault before saving the message or its effects, and the message is
lost.

streamline detection of concurrent operations The following pattern is not reliable::

    if lock.acquire(): pass
    lock.release()

The call to `lock.acquire` could succeed for the current greenlet, while
there are other greenlets waiting for the same lock with
`acquire(blocking=True)`. Under this circunstance the `release` call
would context-switch to the waiting greenlet, and the previous check
would be "invalidated".

Although the current code doesn't use `acquire(blocking=True)`, and the
problem mentioned above wouldn't occur, the code base is left in a
fragile state that is easy to break. This changes the code to only call
acquire once, and to release the lock only after the action is executed.

smoketest: allow geth executable to be specified via RST_GETH_BINARY This fixes a regression introduced in 3658169e0ebd71e9f631175146ac8399388681da.
If an invalid RST_GETH_BINARY path is now specified, smoketest also bails out
early now.

Moved queues to the NodeState Having the message queue in the ChannelState objects makes it necessary
to loop over all channels to get the queues. This is bad because:

- At restart the transport layer needs to be informed of the all
existing queues.
- For a message to be removed from the queue a state change is required,
this state change needs to check all queues, which would require
gathering of all the queues from the netting channel objects. Having all
the queues is a central place makes things easier (the traversal has
really bad complexity and must be improved)

Fix race condition for event handling The `RaidenAPI` calls `RaidenService.poll_blockchain_events` explicitely to
ensure that a transaction recently mined has all the events processed.
This is to update the node state and ensure the user of `RaidenAPI` will
see the expected effects applied.

The problem is that the `AlarmTask` can race with the transaction polling,
and *if* the event handler context-switches the effects may not be
applied once the `RaidenAPI` call returns. The introduced lock will
serialize all calls to `poll_blockchain_events`, forcing the `RaidenAPI`
to wait until the `AlarmTask` finish processing the events.

Note: This change will break if the events are *not* processed in the
`AlarmTask` greenlet.

check problems, e.g.:

    if isintance(obj, StopStateChange):

    elif isintance(obj, StopWithCareStateChange):
        handle_stop_with_care(state, obj)

Where StopWithCareStateChange is a subclass of StopStateChange, in that
case the second branch would never be hit.

Ignore git-tag version on non tagged commits Our version reporting is a little brittle for non-released installs from
git: If there is no tag (yet), but the intended version maintained in
`setup.py::version` is higher than the latest available tag, the version
description will be incorrect.

With this commit, we ignore the tag part on un-tagged git commits, which
allows for a better version resolution, especially during CI (i.e. PRs
for a version bump).

BlockChainService: rpc client as a constructor arg The fixture setup needs a rpc client from a valid account to check for
the eth node state. Because the rpc client keeps the nonce locally the
same object must be reused with the blockchain service, to avoid nonce
synchronization problems. This commit removes the JSONRPCClient
instantiation from inside the BlockChainService, and adds it as a
constructor argument for this reason.

fixture setup using only the deploy service The blockchain fixture/utils was testing the balance of each address
with an unique rpc client, since the rpc client objects store the nonce
as local state, the nonces were not synchronized for the actual test
run. This may be a reason for tests with underpriced transactions
errors.

maybe send ack works needs a running trasport This fixes a regression, a context switch was introduced after the check
for the state of the datagram server, this context switch exposed a race
that allowed a call to `transport.send` on a closed transport.

alarm task stopped before filter uninstall RaidenService had a race among the alarm task and the filter removal,
that allowed the filter to be uninstall before the next poll callback
was
executed, resulting in exceptions like the following:

JSONRPCClientReplyError: filter not found

This change adds synchronization, requiring the alarm task to
completely stop before the events are removed.

Read version information from `git` in `setup.py` This adds `git describe --tags` parsing to `setup.py` in order to create
a more accurate `version` string for the package:
- on tagged commits, it will use the tag as version
- other commits will be displayed as a postrelease version
(according to PEP440), i.e. `0.0.6+git.r0c7f952`
- on errors with git, it will use the plain `version` string defined in
`setup.py` (as managed through bumpversion).

Add `raiden version` command This adds a command and the tooling for displaying system and
installation information. The `raiden version` command output can look like
this:

    {
      "python_version": "2.7.11",
      "python_implementation": "CPython",
      "system": "Linux 64bit_ELF 3.13.0-45-generic",
      "raiden": "0.0.6"
    }

removed lock expiration check from netting channel The netting channel is not at a position to properly check the
expiration of the lock. The expiration of the lock is defined by the
transfer task, and it takes into account the current pending number of
block until settlement, the payer lock.expiration, and the channel
reveal_timeout configuration. Once the function to create the locked
transfer is called the lock expiration was already decremented the
reveal timeout and the additional blocks are not required for safety.

An alternative to remove the check from the netting channel is to
provide the base expiration, and the create_lockedtransfer method then
decrements the reveal_timeout prior to creating the transfer, this
allows the channel and the transfer task that there are the required
number of blocks for safety.

Accept messages with expired locks. - A node may go offline while there are locked transfers in-transit /
waiting confirmation.
- If the node comes back online *after* any of these transfers have
expired, it *must* accept them to allow progress. This happens because
the partner/sender must order the messages to keep the messages
consistent, and the sender has no logic to recompute/removed outdated
messages from the queue. Without accepting outdated messages the
protocol won't make progress.

Note: Accepting a message with an outdated lock is only to progress the
queue, the transfer wont complete because of it, even if the lock is
learned afterwards, and the message wont be mediated because there
isn't enough blocks left to safely mediate a transfer.

Do not invoke contract compilation at file import Until now anything that imported `raiden/blockchain/abi.py` invoked the
compilation of our contracts in order to get the ABI and some other
attributes.

This PR moves the logic to a class that is initialized at import but not
instantiated there. The ABI and other contracts attributes are lazily
evaluated. In other words the first time something is required only then
are the contracts compiled.

Finally now we can do `raiden --help` without waiting 5-6 seconds.

we're in the leaving state, the message handler won't ACK incoming

To grab the lower 8 bits should be `(x & 0xff)`, not `(x & 0x01)`. For
`v` in `[0, 1]` (old versions of geth) this should cause an issue but

Prepare removal of the `our_address` argument The pure python/shared-state implementation of the netting_channel
forced us to use an argument for `our_address` in several
signatures/calls, where it is superflous, because the owners address is
known.

This commit adds a wrapper class around NettingChannelMock, that, once
initiated with a specific address and the NettingChannelMock instance,
fills in the `our_address` argument wherever it is expected, while still
publishing the same interface as NettingChannelMock and keeping the
shared state.

This should allow us to purge `our_address` from all signatures other
than the methods of
`raiden.tests.utils.mock_client.py::NettingChannelMock`.

by receiving transfers, hence the better layer to report is on the
outside implementations that can track the `distributable` amounts.

did report if either channel end was funded, now it checks for the local

Use ConnectionManager per token in RaidenService Per registered token the RaidenService will maintain one ConnectionManager
instance. On channel events, the connection manager will be called to
optimize connectivity.

Add ConnectionManager for automatic channel provisioning The `ConnectionManager` is intended to allow per-token token-network connection
establishment and maintenance.

It provides three functions:

- `connect(funds)` to initialize a connection
- `join_channel(partner_address, partner_deposit)` to join an channel on discovery of
  a newly opened channel
- `retry_connect()` to create more channels on discovery of new network
  participants

The `ConnectionManager` follows a certain fund-splitting strategy (configured
on `__init__(…)`, where a part of the funds is used to open a certain count of
channels right away (which aims at establishing "upstream" connectivity), and
another part is held back in order to join channels that are opened with
oneself from other partners (to establish "downstream" connectivity).

run faster on one machine than another.

This is a problem specially with the build server and new relases of
third-party sofware, since our intent is to force failure for test that
would never finish in one hand, and in another to get a proper output
from the build server, it should be sufficient to have large timeout
that guarantees the later, and for the former a developer can set a flag
on the command line to overwrite the default.

Check available memory before running the geth miner If the system running the tests doesn't have enough memory to keep all
the DAG in the main memory the POW process will be slower than expected,
resulting in test flakiness, specifically for the tests that depend on

geth miner, nothing happens with the purely unit/tester tests.

the test geth arguments.

If there is a reason then then at least the argument should be sanitized

We are lucky geth accepts this at the moment, but this should not be our
default behaviour.

Tweak cached genesis to work with newer geth I am not 100% sure if this is expected behaviour but with latest geth
master custom genesis file parsing is becoming more strict.

If you append the `--blockchain-cache` argument while running the tests
with latest geth then you are bound to hit the same problem.

Make sure to remove all caches before attempting to run this branch. If
you don't you will still load the old cached genesis file. To do that
run the following from the raiden root directory:

`rm -rf /tmp/<username>/pytest-of-<username>/pytest-* && rm -rf .cache `

Naturally replace `<username>` with your username.

In order to have the cached genesis accepted by geth the following were
done:

- Make sure that all hex is prefixed with 0x.
- Nonces must be encoded as hex strings of length 16.
- Storage key/values must be encoded as hex strings of length 64.

I am still waiting for confirmation from the geth developers if this is
here to stay.

Allow to store and use precompiled ABIs This adds tooling to read the contract ABIs from a json file instead of
compiling them at runtime. It will always check the contract source files
against a recorded `sha1` checksum (and compile in case of a mismatch).

The interface for creating the precompiled files is a little funky though. For
precompiling, you should change `raiden.utils.STORE_PRECOMPILED` to `True` and
import `raiden.blockchain.abi`.

    from raiden import utils
    utils.STORE_PRECOMPILED = True
    from raiden.blockchain import abi
    # the import will already trigger compilation and saving

Since this is a packaging operation only, I believe this drawback is okay.

Add more stable nonce-querying to the rpc client In situations with high concurrency there are two potential error conditions
with our current nonce querying method:

1) the remote (blockchain rpc service) may not have updated the pending
transaction count in time
2) two transactions may ask for the transaction count/nonce concurrently

I added a local nonce counter to avoid cases of 1) and added a locking Semaphore
block around the newly introduced `get_nonce` method to avoid cases of 2).

mediator and timeout fixes Timeout fixes:

A node receiving a mediated transfer should not care if the lock
expiratoin is larger than the settlement period, since this doesn't
restrict when the lock may be unlock, i.e. a lock with a large
expiration can be seen as a lock with expiration equal to the settlement
timeout.

- The initiator knowns the secret and doesnt need to take out reveal
timeout from the first mediated transfer, it can send a mediated
transfer with an expiration equal to the channel settlement timeout to
the first hop.
- A mediator may accept a lock with an expiration larger than settlement
timeout and from a channel under settlement, the only requirement is for
the mediator to constraint the expiration of the lock that will be
forwared with the lowest bound (settlement timeout, lock expiration,
number of blocks left until settlement of the channel) and deduct reveal
timeout from it.
- The RefundTransfers are counting like a normal mediated transfer and
the reveal_timeout is taken from lock expiration as usual. Some
tinkering is required to decided if the expiration can be reseted by a
node once all routes fail.

include API-exposure (http-requests), include push-events (socketio) This is the server for the API exposure.
All methods marked by the @expose decorator will be available
via http-requests at the given REST endpoint,
once the Dispatcher is initialized and the server is running.
Synchronous methods will return their return-value immediately
in the request's respond message.
Asynchronous methods will not return their return value,
but rather a unique callback-id, that will later be used
in a 'rpc_response' Event via socket.io for evaluation.

The response is structured like this:

{
    callback_id: value or None if Synchronous
    method= str (the methods name)
    result= value or None if Asynchronous
}

Clients should also connect to the websocket
that is used for push-Notifications ('Events')
via the socket.io protocol.
Without the connection to the socket,
asynchronous calls over http-requests will be initiated,
but the client has no knowledge about the success of the call.
Also externally initiated state-changes such as channel-opening
or incoming transfers will not be observed by the client,
if he doesn't want to pull this information constantly.

Events are structured like this:

    Event:      'rpc_response'
    namespace:  '/'
    data:       {
                    callback_id: <int>,
                    procedure: <str>,
                    status: <bool>
                }

Create release tooling #270 This allows us to create proof of concept releases in as few steps as possible:
On the master branch call

    git checkout master
    git pull --rebase
    git tag <RELEASE_TAG>
    git push --tags

where `x` equals the PoC number. So we should probably switch to `v0.0.x` tags
from the `PoC-x` tags.  Since pypi published versions should already follow this
standard, I believe this inconsistency with our prior PoC releases is okay.

untangle and cleanup raiden.mtree The previous implementation of merkleroot was hard to understand, since
it tried to do several things at the same time.

I've tried to untangle that and now we've got separate functions to
- iterate pairwise over a list of elements
- compute the layers of the merkletree
- create proofs from the merkletree layers

I've also added a Merkletree class, which is initialized with a list of
hashes. This allows to compute multiple proofs for the same tree without
recomputing hashes all the time.

The merkleroot function still exists, but eventually it will be removed.

Secret handling and tasks bugfixes/improvements Messages:
- Added RevealSecret message usage
  For a transfer to complete secrets need to be revealed and for
  consistency reasons state changes to the balance_proof need to be
  controlled by the sender node, the older Secret message was used for
  both reasons, RevealSecret was introduced to only reveal a secret
  without making state changes and the Secret message is intended for
  state updates only.
- (bugfix) Added `amount` and `identifier` checks to the `SecretRequest`
  allowing the initiator to check the `target` received.

Secret Handling:
- Added `register_secret` method in the Raiden class.
  With the introduction of exchanges the same secret might be of
  interest to multiple tasks/channels, this method will register the
  secret with any relevant channel so that proofs can be generated.
- `AssetManager.handle_secret` only removes channels when the lock is
  claimed. Previously the handle_secret would remove the channels on the first
  interation, that meant that a RevealSecret message followed by a Secret
  message would not properly update the channel state.

  The secret handling has the following semantics:
    - if the lock is owned unlock all channels and send the required
      Secret messages (currently only used for transfers that had a Refund, in
      the future this can be used if the transfers are splited)
    - for locks owned by the partner:
	- if not a Secret message, reveal the secret to the partner and
	  wait for the Secret message
	- if it's a Secret message unlock the proper channel end
	  (currently there is at maximum 1 channel, this can be changed
	  for many channels if splited transfers are added)

Tasks:
- (bugfix) Tasks will wait until the lock is claimed not unlocked
  (meaning a Secret message is required instead of just a RevealSecret
  message)
- (bugfix) Tasks receive messages through a Queue instead of an
  AsyncResult. The AsyncResult class can only be set once, resetting
  the task AsyncResult turned out to be unreliable and messages got
  dropped (if a second message is received before the task executed it
  was lost).
- (bugfix) Tasks will wait until the block end before unregistering,
  this needs to be done otherwise a fake Timeout message would turn the
  node clueless about secrets being revelead.
- (bugfix) Start and End tasks will also register the channels for
  hashlock, otherwise the secret handling wont work properly.
- (bugfix) StartExchangeTask will also revel the secret to the node that
  is exchanging asset.
- After the secret is revealed and ACK by the end-of-chain it will also
  propagates forward, this decision simplifies secret handling for nodes
  that are mediating both transfers of an exchange.
- Implemented messages iterators, so that multiple RevealSecret messages
  can be handled without changing the task state.

Channels:
- splited `claim_lock` into `unlock_lock` and `withdraw_lock` to reflect
  the end that can do state update.

Protocol:
- added a queue per asset to avoid unecessary contention.

Other:
- some improvements in pep8, docstrings, and variable names.

added RevealSecret message The `Secret` message was being used to update the partner state and to
reveal the secret to the interest parties, added a new message for just
revealing a secret without the state update semantics.

To allow the `initiator` to check the receiving amount by the `target`,
`amount` was added into the `SecretRequest` message.

`asset` was added in the `Secret` message to force a different echo hash
for the `Secret` messages, important for exchanges were the `secret`
is shared but two assets are involved.

Splitted the method `claim_lock` in two (`withdraw_lock` and
`release_lock`). `release_lock` is used by the sending end of the
channel to update it's own channel, `withdraw_lock` is used by the
receiving end once a state update is received.

Removed hardcoded constantes for expiration timeouts (usually 5), using
`settle_timeout - reveal_timeout`.

Note: the message `RevealSecret` was added to the code base, but the
tasks are not using it yet.

add simple browser based user interface Changes:

The `API` as well as the `TransferManager` now support simple callback handling.
Callbacks are intended to return a (callback_id, status) feedback of requested transfers
from the API on completion of a `MediatedTransferTask`.
This is only supported by mediated transfers, callback handling for direct transfers is still missing.

New Functionality:

A `WebUI` module was added, which supports transfer creation and transfer-status feedback.
The UI can be tested with running the `tests/test_webui.py` (instructions are in the file).
Backend (`web_ui.py` / gevent-websocket) and frontend (`raiden.js` / autobahn.js)
communicate using the WAMP-protocol (v.1), combining RPC-calls and PubSub-events.

To Do:
- implement PubSub messages in raiden base-code for further UI-functionality

Better Decoder discovery Changes:

raiden.encoding.Decoder is a class resposable to do auto discovery of
Message classes, the old code was looking only one level deep in the
subclass hierarchy, missing the message classes MediatedTransfer and
CancelTranfer, this commit adds a graph like search for subclasses that
can cope with arbitrary levels of subclasses.

Decoder now accepts a wider range of integers, because we are
transitioning to a non RLP based encoding
